      "micro_skill": "example_integration_order",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "domain": "academic",
      "prompt": "Order: A: The importance of using specific, quantified examples rather than vague generalisations is illustrated by the difference in persuasive power between these two versions. B: Version 1: 'Poor nutrition affects children's learning.' Version 2: 'A study in 29 US schools found that providing free breakfast to all students reduced chronic absenteeism by 3.4% and improved standardised test scores by 17.5% among the lowest-income students.' C: Version 2 is more persuasive because it specifies the mechanism (breakfast), the population (lowest-income students), and the outcomes (attendance and scores) with measurable precision. D: Effective academic writing uses examples that specify who, what, where, and how much — enabling the reader to assess both the relevance and the reliability of the evidence.",
      "choices": [
        "A-B-C-D",
        "B-A-C-D",
        "C-A-B-D",
        "D-C-A-B"
